    slug: "the-ruling-on-tasweer",
    description: `The Ruling on Tasweer is an Islamic book that provides a thorough and systematic examination of the Islamic legal ruling on image-making (tasweer) and photography, addressing a topic that has become increasingly relevant in the modern era of digital media, social networking, and visual communication. The book collects and analyzes all the relevant hadith narrations that deal with the prohibition or permission of images in Islam, presenting them with their full chains of narration, authenticity gradings, and scholarly interpretations. The author's approach is to examine the evidence comprehensively and present the range of scholarly opinions on this matter, allowing readers to understand the basis for each position and make informed decisions in accordance with their own scholarly preferences.

The book begins by presenting the hadith narrations that appear to prohibit image-making in Islam, including the well-known narrations in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) strongly condemned those who make images and those who keep images in their homes. The author provides a detailed analysis of each narration, examining its chain of transmission (isnad), its text (matn), the circumstances under which it was reported, and the various ways that scholars have interpreted it. The book discusses the famous hadith about the makers of images receiving the severest punishment on the Day of Judgment, and explores the scholarly debate about whether this prohibition applies to all forms of image-making or is restricted to specific types of images such as statues, three-dimensional figures, or images that are objects of veneration.

The book then addresses the questions that arise in the context of modern technology and visual media. Separate chapters examine the Islamic ruling on photography, video recording, digital images, television, cinema, drawings and paintings, children's illustrated books, educational materials, identity photographs, security cameras, medical imaging, and other forms of visual representation that did not exist at the time of the Prophet. The author presents the arguments of scholars who extend the prohibition of image-making to photography and modern visual media, as well as the arguments of scholars who distinguish between hand-drawn images and photographic or digital images. The book also discusses the permissibility of images in certain contexts, such as educational illustrations, historical documentation, and cases of necessity. The various scholarly opinions are presented with their supporting evidence and reasoning, allowing the reader to appreciate the depth of scholarly discussion on this topic. This book is a valuable reference for students of Islamic jurisprudence, scholars, and any Muslim who navigates the complex visual landscape of the modern world.`,
